    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": " Is the radiation dose safe?",
        "answer": " \n Yes. Our scanners use iterative reconstruction to keep exposure as low as reasonably achievable.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": " Can I drive after the scan?",
        "answer": " Absolutely. No sedation is used unless specifically requested."
      },
      {
        "question": "What if my creatinine is borderline?",
        "answer": " We use the CKD-EPI equation; borderline cases receive prophylactic hydration and nephrologist review.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "How soon can I eat?",
        "answer": " Immediately after the observation period; light snacks are provided at the center.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "What is the difference between this and a regular CT abdomen?",
        "answer": "A regular or standard CT abdomen, often done with a single phase of contrast, provides excellent structural detail. However, a **CT Triphasic Abdomen** involves precisely timed imaging during three distinct phases of blood flow. This provides much more functional information about the blood supply to organs and lesions, making it superior for characterizing tumors, especially in the liver and pancreas."
      }
